  "prompt": "Why do people with white skin get burnt easily?",
  "response": "People with lighter skin, often referred to as having \"white skin,\" tend to get sunburned more easily primarily due to lower levels of melanin in their skin. Melanin is the pigment responsible for giving skin its color and provides some protection against ultraviolet (UV) radiation from the sun.\n\nHere are a few reasons why individuals with lighter skin may burn more easily:\n\n1. **Melanin Production:** Lighter-skinned individuals generally produce less melanin compared to those with darker skin. Melanin absorbs and dissipates UV radiation, helping to protect skin cells from damage. Less melanin means less natural protection against sunburn.\n\n2. **Skin Type:** The Fitzpatrick classification system categorizes skin types based on their response to UV exposure. Fair-skinned individuals typically fall into types I or II, which are more prone to burning and have a tendency to tan minimally or not at all.\n\n3. **Thin Skin Structure:** Fair skin is often thinner, which may contribute to greater susceptibility to UV damage compared to thicker, more pigmented skin types.\n\n4. **Cumulative UV Exposure:** Lighter-skinned individuals may not only burn more easily but also may have a higher cumulative risk of skin damage due to UV exposure if they don't take protective measures.\n\n5. **Genetic Factors:** Genetic traits play a significant role in determining how well skin can cope with UV exposure. Individuals with fair skin may have a genetic predisposition that makes their skin less resilient to sun damage.\n\nBecause of these factors, it's crucial for lighter-skinned individuals to take protective measures when exposed to the sun, such as using sunscreen, wearing protective clothing, and seeking shade during peak UV hours. By doing so, they can help reduce their risk of sunburn and long-term skin damage, including the risk of skin cancer.",
